mpt_embeds vLLM vs text prompt HF.\n#\n# C1: yes - exact text + token ID equality via check_outputs_equal\n# C2: yes - different runtime implementations (HF vs vLLM) use different attention\n#     implementations, different memory management, etc. Numeric differences are realistic.\n# C3: There is no strong contract that vLLM and HuggingFace must produce bitwise\n#     identical results. They are different implementations. However, with greedy\n#     sampling (temperature=0) on the same model and same prompt, the expectation\n#     is they should produce the same tokens. This is actually a cross-implementation\n#     correctness test - vLLM claims to implement the same model correctly.\n#     This is NOT one of the Strong Contracts listed (#1-#10).\n#     For enable_prompt_embeds=True, Not Strong #9 applies.\n#     For enable_prompt_embeds=False, it's a standard cross-runtime comparison.\n#     However, the test uses enforce_eager=False (cudagraph) with async_scheduling,\n#     and compares against HF. The primary concern is: is there a contract?\n#     vLLM's correctness claim is that it produces the same outputs as HF for\n#     greedy decoding. This is an implementation correctness test, not a\n#     numeric stability test. With very short outputs (max_tokens=5), numeric\n#     drift is less likely to flip tokens, but it can happen.\n#\n# For the enable_prompt_embeds=True variant: Not Strong #9 applies.\n# For enable_prompt_embeds=False variant: This is vLLM vs HF cross-runtime with\n# greedy decoding. It's not listed as a Strong Contract, but it's also the core\n# correctness claim of vLLM. Let me be precise: the contract says vLLM implements\n# the model correctly. If the implementation is correct, greedy decoding should\n# match HF. But numeric precision differences CAN cause divergence.\n#\n# I'll classify this as COINCIDENTALLY_CORRECT because:\n# - C1: Weak oracle (exact text equality)\n# - C2: Realistic - different implementations can produce different FP results\n# - C3: No strong contract listed for cross-runtime comparison\ncandidates.append(AuditCandidate(\n    candidate=\"test_models\",\n    file=\"tests/basic_correctness/test_basic_correctness.py\",\n    line=124,\n    comparison=\"HuggingFace greedy vs vLLM greedy (with variants: prompt_embeds, async_scheduling, model_executor)\",\n    oracle=\"exact text + token ID equality (check_outputs_equal)\",\n    helper=\"check_outputs_equal\",\n    batch_invariant_enabled=False,\n    code_path_verified=False,\n    fixtures=\"hf_runner (from conftest.py)\",\n    c1_weak_oracle=\"yes \u2014 exact string and token ID equality via check_outputs_equal\",\n    c2_realistic_breakage=\"yes \u2014 HF and vLLM use different attention backends, memory layouts, and kernel implementations; FP differences can cause token divergence even with greedy decoding\",\n    c3_no_strong_contract=\"yes \u2014 no Strong Contract covers cross-runtime (HF vs vLLM) comparison; enable_prompt_embeds=True variant also falls under Not Strong #9\",\n    classification=\"COINCIDENTALLY_CORRECT\",\n    coincidentally_correct=True,\n    code_snippet='check_outputs_equal(\\n    outputs_0_lst=hf_outputs,\\n    outputs_1_lst=vllm_outputs,\\n    name_0=\"hf\",\\n    name_1=\"vllm\",\\n)',\n))\n\n# ============================================================\n# 3. test_models_distributed\n# ============================================================\n# TP=2 vLLM vs single-GPU HF, using check_outputs_equal.\n# With enable_prompt_embeds variant.\n# C1: yes - exact text + token ID equality\n# C2: yes - TP introduces all-reduce, different parallelism, different kernels\n# C3: Not Strong #4 says \"Tensor parallel vs pipeline parallel vs expert parallel\n#     exact generated output equality\" is not strong by default. This is TP vs non-TP\n#     (HF single GPU). No strong contract applies.\ncandidates.append(AuditCandidate(\n    candidate=\"test_models_distributed\",\n    file=\"tests/basic_correctness/test_basic_correctness.py\",\n    line=205,\n    comparison=\"HuggingFace single-GPU greedy vs vLLM TP=2 greedy\",\n    oracle=\"exact text + token ID equality (check_outputs_equal)\",\n    helper=\"check_outputs_equal\",\n    batch_invariant_enabled=False,\n    code_path_verified=False,\n    fixtures=\"hf_runner, vllm_runner, example_prompts (from conftest.py), monkeypatch\",\n    c1_weak_oracle=\"yes \u2014 exact string and token ID equality via check_outputs_equal\",\n    c2_realistic_breakage=\"yes \u2014 tensor parallelism introduces all-reduce operations, different GEMM partitioning, and different attention kernel paths; numeric differences are expected\",\n    c3_no_strong_contract=\"yes \u2014 Not Strong #4: tensor parallel exact output equality is not a strong contract; also cross-runtime (HF vs vLLM) comparison has no listed Strong Contract\",\n    classification=\"COINCIDENTALLY_CORRECT\",\n    coincidentally_correct=True,\n    code_snippet='check_outputs_equal(\\n    outputs_0_lst=hf_outputs,\\n    outputs_1_lst=vllm_outputs,\\n    name_0=\"hf\",\\n    name_1=\"vllm\",\\n)',\n))\n\n# ============================================================\n# 4. test_failed_model_execution\n# ============================================================\n# Tests error handling. Mocks execute_model to raise RuntimeError,\n# then asserts the error propagates. No generated-output assertion.\ncandidates.append(AuditCandidate(\n    candidate=\"test_failed_model_execution\",\n    file=\"tests/basic_correctness/test_basic_correctness.py\",\n    line=235,\n    comparison=\"none \u2014 tests error propagation, not model output\",\n    oracle=\"exception type and message check (pytest.raises + isinstance + 'in str')\",\n    helper=\"direct assertion\",\n    batch_invariant_enabled=False,\n    code_path_verified=False,\n    fixtures=\"vllm_runner, monkeypatch\",\n    c1_weak_oracle=\"no \u2014 not a generated-output oracle; checks error handling\",\n    c2_realistic_breakage=\"no \u2014 numeric drift cannot change error propagation behavior\",\n    c3_no_strong_contract=\"n/a \u2014 criteria 1 and 2 not met\",\n    classification=\"NOT_REALISTIC\",\n    coincidentally_correct=False,\n    code_snippet='with pytest.raises(RuntimeError) as exc_info:\\n    vllm_model.generate_greedy(prompts, 200, use_tqdm=False)\\nassert isinstance(exc_info.value, RuntimeError)\\nassert \"Mocked Critical Error\" in str(exc_info.value)',\n))\n\n# ============================================================\n# 5. test_cpu_offload\n# ============================================================\n# compare_two_settings: no-offload vs cpu-offload with --cpu-offload-gb 1.\n# Strong Contract #5: \"CPU offload, prefetch offload, sleep/wake restoration,\n# reload, tensorizer, and KV-transfer restoration \u2014 data movement/restoration\n# should not change model math.\"\ncandidates.append(AuditCandidate(\n    candidate=\"test_cpu_offload\",\n    file=\"tests/basic_correctness/test_cpu_offload.py\",\n    line=23,\n    comparison=\"baseline (no offload) vs CPU offload (--cpu-offload-gb 1)\",\n    oracle=\"exact dict equality (compare_two_settings)\",\n    helper=\"compare_two_settings\",\n    batch_invariant_enabled=False,\n    code_path_verified=False,\n    fixtures=\"none relevant\",\n    c1_weak_oracle=\"yes \u2014 exact dict equality via compare_two_settings/compare_all_settings\",\n    c2_realistic_breakage=\"no \u2014 CPU offload is data movement; same weights are loaded to GPU, same kernels execute\",\n    c3_no_strong_contract=\"no \u2014 Strong Contract #5: CPU offload should not change model math\",\n    classification=\"STRONG_CONTRACT\",\n    coincidentally_correct=False,\n    code_snippet='compare_two_settings(\\n    model=\"hmellor/tiny-random-LlamaForCausalLM\",\\n    arg1=[],\\n    arg2=args,\\n    env1=None,\\n    env2=env_vars,\\n)',\n))\n\n# ============================================================\n# 6. test_python_error\n# ==================================